IMPACTED SOIL WAS REMOVED/ REMEDIATED. ONE HOUSEHOLD WITHIN 1/4 MILE WAS EVACUATED FOR APPROX. THREE HOURS.

column168: WHEN THE PACKAGE WAS OPENED BECAUSE OF THE SPILL A USFILTER "WASTE PROFILE SHEET" WAS INSIDE IDENTIFYING THE PRODUCT AS RQ WASTE CORROSIVE; ELECTRO POLISHING WITH UN3264 MARKED.  THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND THE PERSON WHO ACTUALLY SHIPPED IT WAS NOT IN BUT THEY THOUGHT IT WAS JUST SAMPLES GOING IN FOR TESTING AND NOT BELIEVED TO BE HAZARDOUS.  ALL DOCUMENTATION THAT WE HAVE ON THE PRODUCT INDICATES HAZARDOUS SO THE FAA WAS CONTACTED AND IS HAVING THE SAMPLE TESTED TO FIND OUT IF IT IS INDEED CORROSIVE.  AT THIS TIME THIS 5800 IS BEING SUBMITTED PRIOR TO THE RESULTS OF THAT TEST IN ORDER TO HAVE A REPORT SUBMITTED WITHIN THE 30 DAY TIME FRAME.  THE PACKAGE IS STILL BEING HELD PENDING THE INVESTIGATION OF THE FAA.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING, ONE LEAKING, TEN GALLON PLASTIC DRUM WAS DISCOVERED IN THE TRAILER.* APPROXIMATELY FOUR GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A LOOSE BUNG. TERMINAL PERSONNEL PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING ABSORBENTS. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO THE TERMINAL'S WASTE RECEPTACLE. THE LEAKING DRUM WAS PLACED INTO A TWENTY FIVE GALLON POLY OVERPACK DRUM AND FORWARDED TO THE SHIPPER'S FACILITY IN FULLERTON, CA. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.* ESTIMATE, CLOSER TO A QUART/PINT

column42: HYDROGEN PEROXIDE, STABILIZED OR HYDROGEN PEROXIDE AQUEOUS SOLUTIONS, STABILIZED WITH MORE THAN 60 PERCENT HYDROGEN PEROXIDE
column62: Fire, Temperature, or Heat; Freezing; Fire, Temperature, or Heat; Water Damage; Water Damage
column168: CONTAINER WAS PICKED UP BY ONYX ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, L.L.C. FROM ATOFINA CHEMICALS, INC. ON 12/28/01 AND TRANSPORTED TO ONYX'S TEN DAY FACILITY IN PHILADELPHIA. DURING THE DAILY INSPECTION PERFORMED AT 1100 AM ON 12/31/01, THIS CONTAINER WAS DISCOVERED AS CHARRED. UPON EXAMINATION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ONE OF THE TWO QUART GLASS BOTTLES CONTAINED IN THE PACKAGE HAD FROZEN AND BURST. THE HYDROGEN PEROXIDE SOLUTION THEN SPILLED OUT OF THE GLASS QUART BOTTLE TO THE OUTER FIBER DRUM CAUSING IT TO SMOLDER AND CHAR. THE SECOND GLASS QUART BOTTLE CONTAINED INSIDE THE PACKAGE WAS UNHARMED BY THE REACTION AND REMAINED IN GOOD INTEGRITY. THE QUART WAS REPACKAGED ALONG WITH THE CLEANUP DEBRIS INTO A 30 GAL 1G(F=DF) FOR PROPER DISPOSAL AND SHIPMENT. NO OTHER PACKAGES IN THE SHIPMENT WERE AFFECTED. FROM THIS POINT ON, ONYX WILL SHIP ALL HYDROGEN PEROXIDE= 20% IN POLY CONTAINERS (1H2) OR OVERPACKED IN A ZIPLOCK BAG PRIOR TO PACKING INTO A FIBER CONTAINER.

column60: Burst or Ruptured; Burst or Ruptured
column168: WHILE LOADING FREIGHT ONTO TRAILER THERE WAS A LOOSE BOX ON TOP OF A PALLET THAT FELL OFF AND LANDED ON THE TRAILER FLOOR. WHEN IT HIT THE FLOOR THE INNER GALLON CONTAINER LID SLIGHTLY POPPED OPENED AND DISCHARGED 1/3 OF IT'S CONTENTS INTO THE OUTER BOX AND THE TRAILER FLOOR. SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED WITH ABSORBENT AND PLACED INTO A RECOVERY CONTAINER ALONG WITH DAMAGED BOX AWAITING FINAL DISPOSITION. THIS COULD HAVE BEEN PREVENTED IF DOCK WORKER HAD INSURED THAT THE BOX WAS PROPERLY SECURED ON THE PALLET PRIOR TO MOVING IT.

A DOCKWORKER WAS TRAVELING ACROSS THE DOCK ON AN ELECTRIC PALLET JACK. HE WAS IN THE AREA WHERE THIS PARTICULAR DRUM WAS AND HE STRUCK A DRUM DOLLY WITH THE ELECTRIC JACK. CONSEQUENTLY, THE DRUM DOLLY SPUN AROUND AFTER IT WAS HIT AND STRUCK AND PUNCTURED THE DRUM STAGED NEXT TO IT. THE DRUM WAS IMMEDIATELY LAID ON ITS SIDE TO STOP FURTHER LEAKAGE AND REPAIRED WITH DRUM PUTTY. THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED WITH ABSORBENT AND PLACED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM ALONG WITH DAMAGED DRUM AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER AS PER INSTRUCTED. THIS COULD HAVE BEEN PREVENTED IF DOCKWORKER WAS PAYING ATTENTION TO THE BIG PICTURE AND WATCHING HIS CLEARANCES.

column42: PRINTING INK, FLAMMABLE OR PRINTING INK RELATED MATERIAL (INCLUDING PRINTING INK THINNING OR REDUCING COMPOUND), FLAMMABLE
column168: WHILE UNLOADING A PALLET FROM A TRAILER, DOCKWORKER STRUCK THE PAIL THAT WAS SITTING ON FLOOR IN FRONT OF PALLET HE WAS UNLOADING WITH THE BLADES OF THE FORKLIFT. CONSEQUENTLY, THE BLADES PUNCTURED THE PAIL RESULTING IN AN UNINTENTIONAL RELEASE. SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED AND CLEANED WITH ABSORBENT AND PUT IN A RECOVERY CONTAINER ALONG WITH DAMAGED CONTAINER AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER AS PER INSTRUCTED.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing; Too Much Weight on Package
column168: WHEN UNLOADING FREIGHT FROM TRAILER DOCKWORKER DISCOVERED ONE BOX THAT WAS WEDGED IN BETWEEN TWO PALLETS THAT WAS APPARENTLY WET AND LEAKING. UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT ONE OF THE QUART CANS HAD BEEN CRUSHED INSIDE CONTRIBUTING TO LEAKAGE. BOX WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE CONTAINER AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER AS PER INSTRUCTED. NO CLEANUP WAS REQUIRED BECAUSE THE BOX ITSELF ABSORBED ALL MATERIAL. THIS COULD HAVE BEEN PREVENTED BY PROPER LOADING AND BLOCKING AND BRACING.

UTLX 68464 NOTED WITH MATERIAL LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR DURING SWITCHING OPERATIONS BY CARRIER PERSONNEL. THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND THE SHIPPER NOTIFIED. CARRIER MECHANICAL REPRESENTATIVES RESPONDED AND FOUND THE MANWAY COVER BOLTS LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT. THE BOLTS WERE PROPERLY TIGHTENED STOPPING THE RELEASE.

THE DRUM WAS BEING TRANSFERRED FROM A VAN TRUCK TO A TRAILER. IT WAS PLACED ON A DOLLY FOR TRANSFER. AS THE MATERIAL WAS BEING MOVED FROM THE VAN TRUCK TO THE TRAILER, IT FELL OFF THE DOLLY AND STRUCK THE GROUND. THE INNER BOTTLES OF HYDROBROMIC ACID BROKE. THE ACID LEAKED OUT OF THE FIBER DRUM AND ONTO THE CONCRETE FLOOR. THE ACID WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH AN ACID SPILL KIT. THE 141G WAS PLACED INTO A 301G WITH A DRUM LINER.   ABSORBANT WAS, ALSO PLACED INTO THE 301G TO PREVENT LEAKAGE. TO PREVENT FUTURE OCCURRENCES, WE WILL PLACE MORE ABSORBENT MATERIAL IN THE BOTTOM OF CONTAINERS FOR BETTER CUSHIONING & ABSORBENCY.

WHILE DELIVERY TO CONSIGNEE WAS BEING MADE PALLET WAS BROKEN DOWN FOR PIECE COUNT AND IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT ONE CARTON OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID HAD LEAKED ONTO THE BOXES BELOW. ONLY LOSS WAS FROM THE CARTON THAT HAD BEEN CRUSHED FORCING ACID FROM THE BOTTLE TOPS AND SPILLING ON TO THE OTHER CARTONS.

column17: CARMAN J A TRUCKING CO INC
column168: VII & VIII ABOVE - NO PACKAGING FAILURE ASSOCIATED WITH THE SPILL.  OUR DRIVER HAD FINISHED MAKING A PUMP DELIVERY OF #2 HEATING OIL TO 10,000 GALLON ABOVE GROUND STORAGE TANK AT THE W.B. HOWARD ELEMENTARY SCHOOL IN NEW LEBANON, NY.  AS OUR DRIVER UNHOOKED THE HOSE FROM THE CUSTOMERS TANK, PRESSURE IN THE LINE CAUSED ABOUT 5 GALLONS OF FUEL TO SPRAY INTO THE AIR. THE FUEL LANDED ON THE TANK, CEMENT UNDER THE TANK, PEASTONE NEXT TO THE TANK AND A SMALL AMOUNT LANDED ON THE BRICK BUILDING AND ROOF SHINGLES. HYDRO TECH WAS CALLED IN TO PERFORM THE CLEAN-UP. NYS DEC WAS NOTIFIED WITH BILL BLAIN PERFORMING THE FOLLOWUP. SPILL OCCURRED BECAUSE THE OVERFILL FLOAT VALVE IN THE TANK CLOSED AS OUR DRIVER WAS BLOWING HIS LINE CLEAR. TANK OVERFILL VALVE IS SET AT 90%, SCHOOL OFFICIALS NOT AWARE OF THIS AND HAD OVER ORDERED.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis
column198: J. A. CARMAN TRUCKING CO., INC.

column168: EMPLOYEE OVERFILLED CARGO TANK. EMPLOYEE PUMPED PART OF THE LOAD BACK INTO THE OIL STOCK TANKS. SPILLAGE WAS BIOREMEDIATED PER THE KANSAS DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH AND ENVIRONMENT.

WHILE TRANSFERRING SHIPMENT AT TRANSFER FACILITY, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT ONE DRUM HAD BEEN OVERFILLED AND THE RING WAS NOT ON AS WELL AS IT SHOULD HAVE BEEN, ALLOWING OIL TO SPILL OVER THE TOP OF THE DRUM AND DOWN THE SIDES. THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED ENTIRELY WITHIN THE CONTAINMENT SYSTEM OF THE TRAILER. PPM LEVEL OF THE MATERIAL WAS ANALYZED AT LESS THAN 25PPM.  REGULAR SPILL CLEAN UP MEASURES WERE FOLLOWED WITH THE LEAKING DRUM BEING PLACED INTO A 85-GAL SALVAGE DRUM. TRANSFER FACILITY PERSONNEL PERFORMED THE CLEAN UP.

TANK CAR UTLX 99235, A RESIDUE LAST CONTAINED, ANHYDROUS AMMONIA, WAS REPORTED TO BE LEAKING VAPORS AND GIVING OFF A STRONG ODOR ON RECEIVING TRACK #4 IN CSX TRANSPORTATION'S (CSXT) RAIL YARD IN AVON, IN. CSXT'S ASST. TERMINAL SUPERINTENDENT ATTEMPTED TO INSPECT THE CAR BUT ODORS WERE TOO STRONG. HE INDICATED HE COULD HEARING A HISSING SOUND COMING FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR. AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR WAS DISPATCHED TO INSPECT THE CAR AND TO MAKE REPAIRS. THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THE INDIANA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT WERE NOTIFIED. THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND THE CONSIGNEE, ROYSTER CLARK WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC. CSXT'S CONTRACTOR DISCOVERED THE VAPOR RELEASE WAS COMING FROM AROUND THE BASE OF THE THERMOMETER WELL CAP WHICH WAS SECURED WRENCH TIGHT. THE CONTRACTOR STOPPED THE VAPOR RELEASE BY WRAPPING THE THERMOMETER WELL WITH DUCT TAPE. MR TIM BROGAN WITH ROYSTER CLARK RESPONDED TO DEPRESSURIZE THE CAR BY DRAWING TH VAPORS OFF INTO A TANKER TRUCK OF WATER. THE TANKER TRUCK OF AMMONIA WATER WAS TAKEN BACK TO ROYSTER CLARK FOR PROCESSING. ROYSTER CLARK OBTAINED A MOVEMENT AUTHORITY, FRA-0112224, FROM THE FEDERAL RAILROAD ADMINISTRATION TO MOVE THE TANK CAR TO THEIR ARCCO. IL FACILITY FOR INSPECTION AND REPAIRS.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, ONE WET FIBERBOARD BOX CONTAINING ONE, ONE QUART GLASS JAR WAS DISCOVERED AT THE FIRST QUARTER MARK OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY ONE QUART OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED AND ABSORBED BY THE FIBERBOARD BOX.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO THE LOAD SHIFTING IN TRANSIT DUE TO IMPROPER LOADING. HAZMAT ONE OF OLATHE, KS WAS CONTACTED AND DISPATCHED HEPACO, INC. TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP.  THE WET FIBERBOARD BOX AND DAMAGED GLASS JAR AND A SECOND, UNDAMAGED BOX THAT WAS DISCOVERED LYING ON ITS SIDE INSIDE THE TRAILER WERE BOTH PLACED INTO A TEN GALLON RECOVERY DRUM, WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  FURTHER CLEAN UP DETAILS WILL BE PROVIDED UPON INVOICING.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, TWO, TWO THOUSAND, ONE HUNDRED AND THIRTY POUND TOTE TANKS WERE DISCOVERED LEAKING AT THE HALFWAY MARK OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY ONE CUP OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  THE RELEASE WAS THE RESULT OF THE CAPS ON THE TOTE TANKS LOOSENING DURING TRANSIT.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM USED GLOVES, AMPHOMAG, A BROOM, A DUST PAN AND ABSORBENT PADS TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A TERMINAL TRASH RECEPTACLE.  THE CAPS ON THE TOTE TANKS WERE TIGHTENED, AND THE TOTE TANKS WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, ONE LEAKING THREE HUNDRED AND THIRTY GALLON POLY TOTE WAS DISCOVERED IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY FIVE GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED.  THE RELEASE WAS A RESULT OF THE BUNG HAVING DETERIORATED.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION, AMPHOMAG, ABSORBENT PADS, A BROOM AND A SHOVEL.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO ONE FIFTEEN GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM, ONE THIRTY-FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM AND TWO FIFTY-FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUMS.  THE FOUR RECOVERY DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE BUNG WAS REPLACED ON THE TOTE AND IT IS BEING HELD AT THE TERMINAL ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT PENDING INSTRUCTIONS FROM THE SHIPPER.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE AT THE CORNER OF LIVERNOIS AND GRAND RIVER AVENUES, IN TRANSIT FROM THE SHIPPER'S WAREHOUSE, THE DRIVER NOTICED FREE PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE REAR OF HIS TRAILER.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, ONE DAMAGED FIFTY-FIVE GALLON METAL DRUM WAS DISCOVERED AT THE HALFWAY MARK OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY FIFTY-FIVE GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASE AND AFFECTED ASPHALT AND A STORM DRAIN.  THE DAMAGE TO THE DRUM WAS DUE TO A LOOSE PALLET JACK PUNCTURING THE DRUM IN THE TRAILER.  THE DETROIT FIRE DEPARTMENT WERE DISPATCHED AND RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  INLAND WATERS POLLUTION CONTROL, INCORPORATED WERE DISPATCHED BY THE DETROIT FIRE DEPARTMENT TO PERFORM THE CLEAN UP.  FURTHER CLEANUP DETAILS WILL BE PROVIDED UPON INVOICING.  ALL STATE AND LOCAL REGULATORY AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, ONE LEAKING FOUR HUNDRED GALLON STEEL TOTE BIN WAS DISCOVERED INSIDE THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY FIVE OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED AND CONTAINED INSIDE THE TRAILER.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A PACKAGING FAILURE.  THE CONSIGNEE, ONDEO NALCO OF SUGAR LAND, TEXAS, WAS CONTACTED TO RESPOND TO THE TERMINAL.  ONDEO NALCO PERSONNEL PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES, GOGGLES, AND RAGS.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A PLASTIC BAG, WHICH WAS REMOVED FROM THE TERMINAL BY THE CONSIGNEE. THE REMAINING PRODUCT INSIDE THE TOTE BIN WAS TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER FOUR HUNDRED GALLON STEEL TOTE BIN, WHICH WAS FORWARDED WITH THE FAULTY TOTE BIN AND THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, ONE LEAKING FIFTY-FIVE GALLON PLASTIC DRUM WAS DISCOVERED AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY ONE TABLESPOON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED ONTO DUNNAGE INSIDE THE TRAILER.  THE DAMAGE TO THE DRUM WAS DUE TO A MISSING BUNG.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING RESPIRATORS, GLOVES, BOOTIES, A DUSTPAN AND A BRUSH.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, AMPHOMAG AND AFFECTED DUNNAGE WERE PLACED INTO A FIFTY-FIVE GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE BUNG ON THE LEAKING DRUM WAS REPLACED AND IT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS RECEIVED.

THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS PLACED INTO A SIXTY GALLON PLASTIC OVERPACK DRUM AND WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT PENDING SHIPPER INSTRUCTIONS.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS RECEIVED.

DURING A ROUTINE FUEL STOP, DRIVER NOTICED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE BACK OF THE TRAILER. DRIVER FOUND THE DRUM IN QUESTION AND TURNED IT ON IT'S SIDE TO STOP THE LEAK. THE CARRIER RETAINED A CONTRACTOR TO RESPOND TO THE SIGHT, OVERPACK THE DAMAGED DRUM, AND CLEAN-UP THE SPILLAGE. CONTRACTOR REPORTED THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK AS A FAILURE OF THE SEAM OF THE DRUM. THE CONTRACTOR OVERPACKED THE DRUM AND PLACED IT BACK ON THE TRAILER, CLEANED THE TRAILER FLOOR, AND DECONTAMINATED THE GROUND. THE FREIGHT WAS DELIVERED WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

column168: DRIVER OF JBK TRACTOR - TRAILER UNIT WAS MAKING A LEFT-HAND TURN WHEN HE SAW AN APPROACHING VEHICLE FROM THE LEFT TRAVELING AT A HIGH RATE OF SPEED. APPROACHING THE VEHICLE WAS A PICK-UP TRUCK, THAT FINALLY APPLIED ITS' BRAKES AND SLID INTO THE BELLY OF THE TRAILER JUST IN FRONT OF THE TANDEM AXLES.  THE IMPACT OF THE PICK-UP CAUSED A 1/4" GAUGE LINE TO BREAK NEAR THE FRONT PRODUCT GAUGE ON THE TRAILER.  THIS ALLOWED A SMALL AMOUNT OF RESIDUAL VAPOR TO ESCAPE TO THE ATMOSPHERE.  THE CARGO TANK HAD JUST BEEN UNLOADED AND CONTAINED A SMALL AMOUNT OF VAPOR ONLY.  WHILE UNDER THE CONTROL OF EMERGENCY RESPONDERS, JBK DRIVER WAS ALLOWED TO VENT THE RESIDUAL PRODUCT VAPOR TO THE ATMOSPHERE TO ALLEVIATE ANY PRESSURE BUILDING CAPABILITIES.  TRACTOR-TRAILER UNIT WAS INSPECTED AND ALLOWED TO BE REMOVED BY THE DRIVER TO HIS TERMINAL IN TUCSON, AZ.  COMPANY MAINTENANCE PERSONNEL WILL EXAMINE THIS CARGO TANK AND REPAIRS WILL BE MADE BY A CERTIFIED REPAIR FACILITY.  THIS ACCIDENT WILL BE REVIEWED BY JBK SAFETY PERSONNEL AND DISCUSSED AT MONTHLY SAFETY MEETINGS.

column168: TANK CAR UTLX 202820 WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING WHEN MOVED BY CSXT HAMLET YARD PERSONNEL. TANK CAR WAS MOVED TO AN ISOLATED AREA OF THE YARD. THE SHIPPER,KOSA WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC OF THE INCIDENT. KOSA CONTRACTED RESCAR TO MAKE THE REPAIRS TO THE TANK CAR. RESCAR TIGHTENED THE STUDS ON THE BOLTED FLANGE FOR THE LIQUID EDUCTION PIPE. THIS SECURED THE TANK CAR. THE TANK CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE IN TRANSPORTATION.

PLMX9111 WAS SUSPECTED OF HAVING A LEAK WHEN A CSXT YARD CREW CONDUCTOR SMELLED AN AMMONIA ODOR WHILE WORKING IN CLOSE PROXIMITY TO THE TANK CAR. YARD WORK IN THE AREA OF THE CAR WAS HALTED UNTIL A CSXT HAZMAT MANAGER COULD EVALUATE THE CAR. THE HAZMAT MANAGER FOUND THE "B" END LIQUID ANGLE VALVE 1/8 TURN FROM BEING TIGHTLY CLOSED. ADDITIONALLY THE THE PRODUCT VALVE PLUGS WERE NOT HAND TIGHT. THE PLUGS WERE TOOL TIGHTENED. CONTACT WAS MADE TO THE SHIPPER VIA CHEMTREC. THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT.

A CSXT TRAIN CREW, WHILE HANDLING GATX 50025, OBSERVED WHITE VAPORS COMING FORM THE TOP OF THE TANK CAR. THE TRAIN CREW IMMEDIATELY SET THE CAR OUT IN AN ISOLATED AREA. ONCE THE TANK CAR WAS STATIONARY THE EMISSION OF VAPORS CEASED. THE YARD MASTER NOTIFIED THE CSXT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT WHO IN TURN NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER AND REQUESTED CORRECTIVE ACTION BE TAKEN TO INSPECT AND REPAIR ANY DEFECTS FOUND. THE SHIPPER HAD A REPAIR CREW RESPOND AND FOUND THAT THE FOUR BOLTS ON THE MANWAY FILL HOLE COVER WERE LOOSE. THE LOOSE BOLTS ALLOWED VAPORS AND A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID TO ESCAPE FROM THE FILL HOLE OPENING. THE BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED AND THE TOP SURFACE OF THE TANK WAS CLEANED. NO OTHER DEFECTS WERE FOUND AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT.

column62: Derailment; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: AT 1855 HRS IN CSX TRANSPORTATION, INC'S (CSXT) RICE YARD IN WAYCROSS GA, TANK CAR, PLMX 340003, A RESIDUE LAST CONTAINED ANHYDROUS AMMONIA, WAS STRUCK BY ANOTHER RESIDUE ANHYDROUS AMMONIA CAR, PLMX 3972 ON TRACK B 35 IN THE CLASS YD. THE COUPLER ON THE PLMX 3972 RODE UP OVER THE COUPLER ON THE PLMX 340003 AND PUNCHED A 3 FT X 3 FT HOLE IN THE B END OF THE PLMX 340003 RESULTING IN THE RELEASE OF AMMONIA VAPORS. THE COLLISION CAUSED THE A END TRUCKS ON PLMX 3972 TO COME LOOSE AND ROLL BACK UP UNDER THE CAR. RAILROAD PERSONNEL WERE REMOVED FORM THE AREA. LOCAL FIRE, AND POLICE DEPARTMENTS WERE NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. THERE WAS NO RELEASE OF PRODUCT OFF CSXT PROPERTY AND NO PUBLIC EVACUATION WAS CALLED. THE GEORGIA EPD AND THE NRC WERE ALSO NOTIFIED. CSXTS HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT AND AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR RESPONDED. A HI RAIL CRANE WAS USED TO SEPARATE THE CARS WITH NO ADDITIONAL AMMONIA RELEASE. THE HOLE IN THE END OF THE PLMX 340003 WAS PLUGGED TO REDUCE THE FURTHER RELEASE OF VAPORS LEFT IN THE TANK. THE PLMX 3972 WAS RERAILED AND THE PLMX 340003 WAS MOVED TO THE "BUMPER" TRACK. AIR MONITORING WAS CONDUCTED DURING THE ENTIRE OPERATION. NO HARMFUL LEVELS OF AMMONIA VAPORS WERE DETECTED. ON 12/11/01, CSXT'S CONTRACTOR FLUSHED THE PLMX 340003 WITH WATER AND USED AN EXHAUST FAN TO REMOVE RESIDUAL VAPORS FORM THE CAR. THE CAR WAS CLEANED AND PURGED OF RESIDUAL MATERIAL ON 12/14/01. REPAIRS WILL BE MADE TO PLMX 340003 AT THE WAYCROSS YARD AND THE CAR WILL THEN BE SENT TO HOME SHOP FOR REPAIRS.

A CSXT TRAIN CREW OPERATING AS Y12218 ENTERED THE E.R. CARPENTER FACILITY FOR THE PURPOSE OF PLACING A LOADED TANK CAR IN THE CUSTOMER'S FACILITY AND REMOVING EMPTY TANK CARS. THE TRAIN CREW COUPLED ONTO GATX 63919 FOR THE PURPOSE OF MOVING THE CAR OUT SO AS TO GAIN ACCESS TO THE EMPTY TANK CAR THAT WAS SPOTTED BEHIND GATX 63919. UNBEKNOWNEST TO THE CREW, GATX 63919, WAS STILL CONNECTED TO THE OFF LOADING HOSES. THE TRAIN CREW REPORTED THAT THE DERAILS ON THE TRACKS LEADING TO THE LOADING RACK WERE IN THE OFF POSITION AND NO "TANK CAR CONNECTED" (BLUEFLAGS) WERE DISPLAYED ON THE TRACKS WHERE THE SUBJECT CAR WAS LOCATED. THE TANK CAR WAS BEING OFFLOADED AT THE TIME WHEN THE TRAIN CREW COUPLED TO THE CAR AND WAS PRESSURIZED WITH COMPRESSED AIR. WHEN THE TANK CAR WAS PULLED BACK, THE OFFLOADING HOSE (2"LIQUID) DISCONNECTED FORM THE GTANK CAR AND BEGAN TO SPEW LIQUID PRODUCT FORM THE BROKEN CONNECTION. THE TRAIN CREW IMMEDIATELY LEFT THE AREA TO PREVENT EXPOSURE TO THE PRODUCT THAT HAD SPILLED. EMPLOYEES OF E.R. CARPENTER THEN INTIATED ACTIONS TO STOP THE RELEASE OF THE MATERIAL AND SECURE THE AREA. THE VAST MAJORITY OF THE PRODUCT SPILLED WAS CONTAINED ON THE SURFACE OF AN ASPHALT PARKING LOT IMMEDIATELY ADJACENT TO THE TRACKS AND THE TANK CAR. A MINOR QUANITIY OF THE MATERIAL ENTERED A STORM DRAIN AND FLOWED OFF THE PLANT PROPERTY TO A SMALL CREEK, EAST OF THE PLANT. LACAL FIRE DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL CONTAINED THE SPILLED MATERIAL IN THE CREEK AND AN ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR WAS CALLED TO RECOVER THE SPILLED PRODUCT ON THE PARKING LOT AND IN THE CREEK.

column168: BNSF SWITCH CREW REPORTED TANK CAR THAT WAS STANDING ON HUMP TRACK RELEASING PRODUCT. BNSF MECHANICAL RESPONDER FOUND PRODUCT RELEASING FORM THE UNCAPPED OUTLETS FOR THE INTERNAL HEATER COIL SYSTEM. NO PRODUCT TRAIL ON THE GROUND WAS APPARENT. RESPONDER INSERTED WOODEN PLUGS INTO THE EXTERNAL ORIFICES OF THE STEAM OUTLET NOZZLES TO ELIMINATE PRODUCT RELEASE. BOTH OUTLET NOZZLE CAPS & THREADS APPEARED TO BE IN USEABLE CONDITION. TANK CAR SPOTTED TO FUEL UNLOADING LOCATION &  REMAINING PRODUCT OFF-LOADED. SPILLED PRODUCT VACUUMED FORM IMPACTED SOIL. HEAVY RAINFALL DURING THIS EVENT RESULTED IN SPILLED PRODUCT WASHING INTO A STORM DRAIN THAT EVENTUALLY REACHED THE WATERS OF PUGET SOUND WHERE A BOAT WITH A BOOM & SKIMMER AWAITED. AN ESTIMATED 3460 GALLONS OF PRODUCT RECOVERED FORM BOTH SOIL & WATER THUS FAR. THE NOW RESIDUE TANK CAR WAS DIRECTED TO A CERTIFIED REPAIR SHOP FOR ROOT CAUSE ANALYSIS OF THE CATASTROPHIC BREACH IN THE INTERNAL HEATER COIL SYSTEM & FURTHER REPAIRS. BNSF SYSTEM INSTRUCTIONS ISSUED TO ENSURE THAT ALL BNSF FUEL CARS HAVE THE INTERNAL HEATER COIL SYSTEM OUTLETS CAPPED & TOOL TIGHTENED DURING ANY TRANSPROTATION PHASE TO ELIMAINATE FUTURE OCCUIRRENCES OF THIS TYPE.

column168: (A) TANK CAR UTLX 200052 WAS PART OF CSXT TRAIN B99123 WHEN IT DERAILED. THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE ON THE TANK CAR STRUCK BY ANOTHER OBJECT CAUSING THE BASE OF THE DEVICE TO BE PUSHED LOOSE OF ITS MOUNTING. THREE OF THE MOUNTING BOLTS WERE BENT AND/OR BROKEN. A QUARTER INCH GAP BETWEEN BASE OF THE DEVICE AND THE MOUNTING FLANGE RESULTED FROM THE IMPACT. THE GAP BETWEEN THE DEVICE AND MOUNTING BASE ALLOWED PRODUCT TO ESCAPE FROM BELOW THE DEVICE. A PLASTIC BAG AND CAULKING MATERIAL WAS USED TO TEMPORARILY SEAL THE DEVICE, SO THAT THE TANK CAR COULD BE MOVED TO AN UPRIGHT POSITION THE CONTENTS OF THE TANK CAR WERE THEN TRANSFERRED TO TRUCKS FOR DELIVERY TO THE CONSIGNEE. (B) TANK CAR ACFX 94414 WAS INVOLVED IN THE DERAILMENT OF CSXT TRAIN B99123. THE TANK CAR WAS STRUCK IN THE "B" END OF THE TANK AND IN THE LEFT SIDE. THE "B" END PUNCTURE WAS APPROXIMATELY 2-4" IN DIAMETER AND EXTENDED FROM THE 6 O'CLOCK  TO THE 9 O'CLOCK POSITION. THE TEAR IN THE LEFT SIDE OF THE CAR WAS 6-10" WIDE AND APPROXIMATELY 5-6 FEET LONG. PRODUCT WAS RELEASED FROM BOTH THE END AND SIDE OF THE CAR. AN ADJACENT TANK CAR OF ACETONE WAS ON FIRE AND PORTION OF THE RELEASED DICHLOROMETHANE MAY HAVE BEEN CONSUMED BY THE FIRE. A PORTION OF THE CAR'S LADING REMAINED IN THE CAR. THE REMAINING PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED INTO TRUCKS AND TRANSPORTED TO A HAZARDOUS WASTE DISPOSAL FACILITY. (C) TANK CAR UTLX 200081 WAS INVOLVED IN THE DERAILMENT OF CSXT TRAIN B99123. DURING THE DERAILMENT THE "A" END OF THE TANK CAR WAS STRUCK BY THE COUPLERS OF ADJACENT RAILCARS AND POSSIBLY OTHER DEBRIS. THIS ACTION CAUSED PUNCTURES IN THE "A" END OF THE TANK AT THE 10 O'CLOCK POSITION OF APPROXIMATELY 4" W X 10"L IN SIZE AND AT THE 8 O'CLOCK POSITION OF APPROXIMATELY 3" X 3" IN SIZE. THERE WAS ALSO A PUNCTURE IN THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE TANK SHELL OF APPROXIMATELY 3" X 3" IN SIZE. PRODUCT WAS RELEASED FROM THE CAR THROUGH THESE HOLES AND THE PRODUCT SUBSEQUENTLY IGNITED AND BURNED FOR APPROXIMATELY 2 HOURS. SOME PRODUCT REMAINED IN THE CAR. THE REMAINING PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED INTO TRUCKS AND TAKEN TO A HAZARDOUS WASTE DISPOSAL  FACILITY. A TOTAL OF APPROXIMATELY 14,000 GALLONS OF ACETONE WAS EITHER BURNT OR RELEASED ONTO THE GROUND.

THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE ON THE TANK CAR STRUCK BY ANOTHER OBJECT CAUSING THE BASE OF THE DEVICE TO BE PUSHED LOOSE OF ITS MOUNTING. THREE OF THE MOUNTING BOLTS WERE BENT AND/OR BROKEN. A QUARTER INCH GAP BETWEEN BASE OF THE DEVICE AND THE MOUNTING FLANGE RESULTED FROM THE IMPACT. THE GAP BETWEEN THE DEVICE AND MOUNTING BASE ALLOWED PRODUCT TO ESCAPE FROM BELOW THE DEVICE. A PLASTIC BAG AND CAULKING MATERIAL WAS USED TO TEMPORARILY SEAL THE DEVICE, SO THAT THE TANK CAR COULD BE MOVED TO AN UPRIGHT POSITION THE CONTENTS OF THE TANK CAR WERE THEN TRANSFERRED TO TRUCKS FOR DELIVERY TO THE CONSIGNEE. (B) TANK CAR ACFX 94414 WAS INVOLVED IN THE DERAILMENT OF CSXT TRAIN B99123. THE TANK CAR WAS STRUCK IN THE "B" END OF THE TANK AND IN THE LEFT SIDE. THE "B" END PUNCTURE WAS APPROXIMATELY 2-4" IN DIAMETER AND EXTENDED FROM THE 6 O'CLOCK  TO THE 9 O'CLOCK POSITION. THE TEAR IN THE LEFT SIDE OF THE CAR WAS 6-10" WIDE AND APPROXIMATELY 5-6 FEET LONG. PRODUCT WAS RELEASED FROM BOTH THE END AND SIDE OF THE CAR. AN ADJACENT TANK CAR OF ACETONE WAS ON FIRE AND PORTION OF THE RELEASED DICHLOROMETHANE MAY HAVE BEEN CONSUMED BY THE FIRE. A PORTION OF THE CAR'S LADING REMAINED IN THE CAR. THE REMAINING PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED INTO TRUCKS AND TRANSPORTED TO A HAZARDOUS WASTE DISPOSAL FACILITY. (C) TANK CAR UTLX 200081 WAS INVOLVED IN THE DERAILMENT OF CSXT TRAIN B99123. DURING THE DERAILMENT THE "A" END OF THE TANK CAR WAS STRUCK BY THE COUPLERS OF ADJACENT RAILCARS AND POSSIBLY OTHER DEBRIS. THIS ACTION CAUSED PUNCTURES IN THE "A" END OF THE TANK AT THE 10 O'CLOCK POSITION OF APPROXIMATELY 4" W X 10"L IN SIZE AND AT THE 8 O'CLOCK POSITION OF APPROXIMATELY 3" X 3" IN SIZE. THERE WAS ALSO A PUNCTURE IN THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE TANK SHELL OF APPROXIMATELY 3" X 3" IN SIZE. PRODUCT WAS RELEASED FROM THE CAR THROUGH THESE HOLES AND THE PRODUCT SUBSEQUENTLY IGNITED AND BURNED FOR APPROXIMATELY 2 HOURS. SOME PRODUCT REMAINED IN THE CAR. THE REMAINING PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED INTO TRUCKS AND TAKEN TO A HAZARDOUS WASTE DISPOSAL  FACILITY. A TOTAL OF APPROXIMATELY 14,000 GALLONS OF ACETONE WAS EITHER BURNT OR RELEASED ONTO THE GROUND.

EMPLOYEES OF LONG'S TRANSFER CALLED LOCAL FIRE AND POLICE DEPARTMENTS TO INVESTIGATE A STRONG AMMONIA ODOR IN THEIR WORK AREA. THE ORDER WAS ATTRIBUTED TO GATX 03405, A RESIDUE TANK CAR OF ANHYDROUS AMMONIA. THE CONSIGNEE, CHEVRON CHEMICAL RESPONDED AT THE REQUEST OF THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT. CHEVRON FOUND THE NEEDLE VALVE ON THE SAMPLE LINE OPEN AND THE PLUG LOOSE. ADDITIONALLY THEY FOUND THE PLUGS LOOSE ON THE VAPOR AND LIQUID LINES. CHEVRON CLOSED THE OPEN VALVE AND TIGHTENED THE PLUGS.

TRUCK ARRIVED AT CUSTOMERS LOCATION. DRIVER AND DRIVER TRAINEE STARTED TO HOOKUP. DRIVER CHECKED THE TRAVEL AND THEY STARTED TO PUMP OFF. AFTER ABOUT FIFTEEN MINUTES, THEY SAW THE DUST CAP ON THE RIGHT SIDE DISCHARGE CAME OFF. THEY STOP PUMPING AND CONTACTED THE OIL COMING OFF THE TRUCK. IN DOING SO, SOME OIL SPRAY INTO THE TRAINEE'S  EYES. HE WAS TAKE TO THE HOSPITAL. AFTER AN INVESTIGATION, IT WAS FOUND THAT THE TRAINEE HAD PLACED THE WRONG DUST CAP ON THE RIGHT DISCHARGE THE LOAD BEFORE.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE ON THE DOCK FOUR WET CARTONS EACH CONTAINING FOUR, ONE GALLON PLASTIC JUGS  WERE DISCOVERED. FURTHER INVESTIGATION DETERMINED THAT TWO JUGS WERE LEAKING AND THE REMAINING FOURTEEN WERE UNAFFECTED. APPROXIMATELY, ONE-HALF GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO LOOSE LIDS. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES AND GOGGLES. THE WET CARTONS AND CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A FIFTEEN GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE LIDS WERE TIGHTENED ON THE LEAKING JUGS AND THE JUGS WERE REPACKAGED. THE CARTONS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL PENDING SHIPPER INSTRUCTIONS.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: A FARMER WAS DRIVING TWO NH3 NURSE TANKS AND AN APPLICATOR TO HIS FIELD WITH A  TRACTOR THE WHEELS ON ONE OF THE NURSE TANKS GOT "PULLED" BY THE LOOSE GRAVEL ON THE SIDE OF THE ROAD CAUSING A "TIP OVER". AS THE TANK ROLLED OVER, THE PROTECTIVE CAGE SURROUNDING THE VALVES ON THE TOP OF THE TANK WAS DAMAGED AND THE WITHDRAWAL VALVE WAS DAMAGED. THE TANK LANDED ON IT'S SIDE WITH THE VALVES TOWARD THE ROAD. THE MAXWELL FIRE DEPT. WAS IMMEDIATELY CALLED.  TWO HEARTLAND CO-OP EMPLOYEES SHORTLY AFTER THE F.D.  BECAUSE LIQUID WAS SPRAYING OUT ONTO THE VALVES, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE SAFEST WAY TO DEAL WITH THE RELEASING TANK WAS TO LET IT "RUN IT'S COURSE".  AFTER THE TANK WAS EMPTY, THE F.D. LEFT THE SCENE. A TOWER HAULED THE TANK TO THE NEAREST HEARTLAND LOCATION. THE DIRT IN THE IMMEDIATE AREA OF THE RELEASE WAS ESCALATED TO BELOW FROST LEVEL AND APPLIED TO THE ADJACENT FARMER'S FIELD. CLEAN UP WAS COMPLETED ON THE SAME DAY AS THE ACCIDENT. RECOMMENDATIONS FOR THE FUTURE:  REMIND FARMERS TO DRIVE CAREFULLY WITH LOADS OF NH3.

APPROX. 5 SECONDS AFTER THE HORN HE FELT THE IMPACT ON THE RIGHT SIDE OF HIS TRAILER. INDUSTRIAL AND ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES WERE CONTRACTED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILLED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. THE MATERIAL WAS THEN REMOVED TO THEIR SITE AT 7551 E. MELTON ROAD, GARY, INDIANA AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER FOR REPROCESSING. OUR UNIT WAS TOTALED AT THE SCENE AND DISPOSED OF BY OUR INSURANCE CARRIER.
THE DRUM WAS PART OF A HEAVY WEIGHT LOAD AND WAS PUNCTURED BY A FORKLIFT UPON UNLOADING. THE DRUM WAS OVERPACKED IN A SALVAGE DRUM AWAITING DISPOSITION FROM SHIPPER/RECIPIENT.

PART TIME HAZMAT TECHNICIANS CECELIA HICKEY AND WILLIAM HENDERSON DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED. UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND A BROWN FIBERBOARD BOX THAT WAS SUSPECTED TO BE LEAKING. THEY REMOVED THIS FROM THE AREA AND BEGAN THEIR INVESTIGATION. UPON THIS INVESTIGATION THEY FOUND THIS BOX TO CONTAIN 1X1 L PLASTIC BOTTLE WITH PLASTIC FRICTION TYPE CLOSURE WHICH DID NOT HAVE POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE RESULTING IN THE LEAKAGE OF APPROXIMATELY 4 OUNCE. THIS DID NOT CONTAIN ABSORBENT MATERIAL. THEY REPLACED THE ITEMS INTO THE BOX, RESEALED IT AND PLACED IT INTO 2 PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL. THEY PLACED THE BAGGED SHIPMENT INTO A RECOVERY DRUM AND FORWARDED THIS DRUM ONTO IT'S DESTINATION. THIS DID HAVE PROPER MARKING, LABELS, AND THE APPROPRIATE HAZ CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANYING IT. A COPY OF THE SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS WILL ACCOMPANY THIS REPORT. CLEAR OF SCENE 0130.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: IMPROPER LOADING RESULTED IN A SHIFT OF THE FREIGHT IN TRANSIT WHICH CAUSED A RELEASE OF THE PRODUCT. ALL SPILLED PRODUCT WAS ABSORBED WITH OIL DRY AND PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM. ALL DAMAGED PRODUCT WAS HANDLED ACCORDING TO ALL LOCAL, STATE AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS. INSTRUCTIONS HAVE BEEN GIVEN AND CORRECTIVE ACTIONS TAKEN FOR ALL EMPLOYEES INVOLVED IN THE RELEASE.

AS WE WERE SORTING PACKAGES FOR THE OUTBOUND A FEDEX EMPLOYEE NOTICED SMOKE EMINATING FROM THE BOX. THE BOX WAS QUICKLY REMOVED FROM THE SORT, SEGREGATED FROM THE REMAINING FREIGHT AND OPENED. WHILE THERE WERE NO VISIBLE FLAMES SHOOTING FROM THE BOX IT WAS READILY APPARENT THAT THE INNER CONTENTS (STRIKE-ANYWHERE MATCHES) HAD CONTRIBUTED TO THE CONFLAGRATION. THE BOX CONTAINED THE AFOREMENTIONED MATCHES, A PIECE OF POLISHED WOOD WITH A STONE IN IT (ALLEGEDLY FOR THE EXPRESSED PURPOSE OF THE MATCHES). ALL OF THAT WAS PACKED WITH SHEARED PAPER FOR CUSHIONING. THE FREIGHT WAS HELD WHILE THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED & COULD INSPECT THE SHIPMENT. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED WHO ADMITTED IT WAS A PERSONAL CHRISTMAS GIFT. THIS SHIPPER ALLOWED THEIR EMPLOYEES TO UTILIZE THEIR FEDEX DISCOUNT FOR PERSONAL SHIPPING THAT PRACTICE HAS BEEN DISCONTINUED. THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELING, SHIPPING PAPERS OR OTHER INDICATORS TO LEAD US TO BELIEVE THE CONTENTS WERE  REGULATED.

DURING THE SORT THE BOX WAS FOUND TO BE GIVING OFF A STRONG ALCOHOL-BASED ODOR. THE BOX WAS OPENED TO REVEAL TWO BOTTLES OF PERFUME. THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED AS THE PERFUME IS FLAMMABLE & THE PACKAGE HAD NO MARKINGS, LABELING, SHIPPING PAPERS OR OTHER INDICATORS TO LEAD US TO BELIEVE THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED. THE SHIPPER, I SPOKE TO MIKE, ADVISED THEY HAVE BEEN SHIPPING LIKE THIS FOR THE PAST TWO YEARS. I ASKED IF THEY HAD A DOT EXEMPTION,  MIKE HAD IN INFORMATION ON THAT IN ADDITION MIKE THOUGHT THAT THE AMOUNT OF PERFUME SHIPPED NULLIFIED THE REQUIREMENT TO DECLARE THE CONTENTS.  THE FREIGHT WAS HELD FOR AN FAA INSPECTION.

column168: CSX TRANSPORTATION RECEIVED A NOTIFICATION FROM QUALITY CARRIERS IN CHESNEE, SC THAT UTLX 66337, LOAD POTASSIUM HYDROXIDE, WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE AT THEIR FACILITY. CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MANAGER TALKED WITH MR JOEL SNIPES AT QUALITY CARRIERS. MR SNIPES ADVISED THAT THE CAR HAD A STEADY DRIP AT THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE'S OPERATING STEM. THEIR PERSONNEL STOPPED THE LEAK BY TIGHTENING THE PACKING GLAND NUT AT THE VALVE STEM. CSXT DELIVERED THIS CAR TO QUALITY CARRIERS IN MID OCTOBER.  THE SHIPPER, OCCIDENTAL CHEMICAL, WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: CUSTOMER WAS UNLOADING TOTE FROM ECOLAB TRUCK USING THEIR FORKLIFT AND FORKLIFT OPERATOR.  THE DOCK IS HIGHER THAN THE TRUCK SO THE FORKLIFT OPERATOR WAS BACKING UPHILL.  THE TOTE CAME OFF THE FORKS AND FELL FORWARD INTO ITS SIDE.  PRODUCT BEGAN TO LEAK FROM TOP OF THE TOTE.  THE TRUCK BECAME SLIPPERY AND THE FORKLIFT COULD NOT BE USED TO UPRIGHT THE TOTE. THE ECOLAB DRIVER USED HIS SPILL KIT TO DIKE THE SPILL ON THE TRUCK.  THE CUSTOMER WAS DEALING WITH THE SPILL OUTSIDE THE TRUCK.  THE DRIVER THEN CALLED THE PLANT TO REPORT THE INCIDENT TO MARIE POWELL, MIKE SCHMIDT, AND MIKE WASHINGTON.  THE DRIVER REPORTED THAT NO ONE WAS INJURED IN THE INCIDENT.  HE ALSO REPORTED WHAT THE OTHER PRODUCTS WERE THAT WERE ON THE TRUCK.  THERE WERE 6 PIECES OF CORROSIVE PRODUCT ON THE TRUCK, WHICH WERE ON PALLETS AND WOULD NOT CO-MINGLE WITH THE ORGANIC PEROXIDE.  THE DRIVER STATED THAT PRODUCT WAS ON THE GROUND, AND THAT THERE WAS A DRAIN IN THE PARKING LOT.  HE WAS INSTRUCTED TO KEEP THE PRODUCT FROM GOING IN THE DRAIN, AND ASKED TO HAVE THE CUSTOMER'S SAFETY MANAGER CONTACT MIKE WASHINGTON.  A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS FAXED IMMEDIATELY TO THE CUSTOMER, ALTHOUGH THEY DID HAVE THE MSDS ON FILE.  MIKE WASHINGTON WORKED WITH THE CUSTOMER AND CALLED A HAZMAT TEAM IN TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL AND THE TRUCK.  MIKE ALSO CONTACTED CHARLES NOTE.  MARIE POWELL CONTACTED ECOLAB SALES REP, JACK HALL.  JACK REPORTS THAT THERE WAS NO PLANT EVACUATION, AND NO PRODUCTION DOWNTIME AS A RESULT OF THE INCIDENT.  JACK WILL MEET WITH CENTENNIAL FARMS' SAFETY MANAGER EITHER LATE 12/14 OR ON 12/17 TO DISCUSS THE INCIDENT.  JACK WILL PROVIDE MARIE POWELL WITH DETAILS OF INCIDENT.

CF PERSONNEL PLACED ABSORBENT ON THE FREE LIQUID. MR. TUCKER STATED THEY NEED TO WATCH THE SUBSTANCE DUE ITS ABILITY TO CATCH ON FIRE WHEN EXPOSED TO MOISTURE. MR. TUCKER CONTACTED CHEMTREC. TUCKER STATED THE SHOULD USE GLOVES AND PLACE THE CARDBOARD BOX CONTAINING THE SPILLED MATERIAL INTO A DRUM AND PLACE OIL ON THE TOP. FISHER SCIENTIFIC CONTACTED MR. TUCKER.  WE DISCUSSED THE CURRENT PLAN OF ACTION. EVERYONE AGREED. DISPOSAL IS PENDING. ALL PACKAGING CODES WERE NOT AVAILABLE.

INVESTIGATION REVEALED A SAMPLE LINE VALVE TO BE ENCASED IN ICE.  AFTER REMOVAL OF ICE, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE SAMPLE LINE WAS OPEN.  THE VALVE WAS CLOSED AND THE ASSEMBLY WAS CHECKED FOR FURTHER LEAKS.  THE SAMPLE LINE VALVE WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING AT THE BASE WHERE IT THREADS ONTO THE NIPPLE COMING FROM THE PRESSURE PLATE. column168: 12-28-01-  EASTERN PETROLEUM DELIVERED 237.6 GALS. OF HOME HEATING OIL. 12-31-01- CUSTOMER CALLED IN SAYING THEY HAD A STRONG OIL SMELL.  WE DISPATCHED LEON WHITE TO THE SITE. HE LOOKED @ THE OIL TANK THAT WAS LOCATED UNDER THE CUSTOMER'S DECK, IT WAS TIGHT AGAINST THE RAFTERS OF THE DECK AND THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK, INCLUDING THE OIL VALVE WAS NOT VISIBLE DUE TO BEING BURIED IN THE DIRT.  LEON DID NOT SEE ANY EVIDENCE OF AN OVERFILL. THERE WAS NO OIL ON TOP OF THE OIL TANK OR ON THE SIDES OF THE TANK. THE RAFTERS ABOVE THE OIL TANK, THAT WERE RIGHT AGAINST THE TOP OF THE OIL TANK, DID NOT HAVE ANY OIL ON THEM. LEON OFFERED TO REMOVE THE JUNK OUT FROM UNDER THE DECK TO FURTHER INVESTIGATE TO SEE WHAT WAS ACTUALLY LEAKING. THE CUSTOMER, AT THAT POINT, TOLD LEON NOT TO DO ANYTHING, THAT THEY WOULD HAVE A CONTRACTOR THAT THEY KNEW TAKE CARE OF IT. LEON CALLED THE SHOP REPORTING THAT THE OIL TANK ITSELF WAS LEAKING OR THE TANK VALVE WAS LEAKING BUT COULD NOT BE SURE BECAUSE THE CUSTOMER WOULD NOT LET HIM INVESTIGATE ANY FURTHER. WE REPORTED THE INCIDENT TO THE DEPT. OF THE ENVIRONMENT.  TO A LADY NAMED NANCY.  1-16-02- EASTERN PETROLEUM RECEIVED A CALL FROM NICK K., WHO IS WITH MDE, THAT HE WAS ON SITE AND HE SAW NO EVIDENCE THAT WOULD INDICATE AN OVERFILL. THERE WERE NO STAINS ON THE OIL TANK OR ANY FRESH OIL ON THE GROUND UNDER OR AROUND THE TANK. THE ONLY THING THAT WAS EVIDENT WAS THAT THE GROUND WAS OIL SOAKED .  HE STATED THAT BECAUSE HE COULD NOT FIGURE OUT WHAT ELSE COULD HAVE CAUSED IT HE WAS REPORTING IT AS A OVERFILL. WE SENT LEON OUT TO MEET NICK. LEON ARRIVED ON SITE AND THE CONTRACTOR HAD ALREADY REMOVED DIRT AND TOLD NICK THAT HE HAD CLEANED OFF THE TANK. LEON TOLD NICK THAT WHEN HE HAD BEEN THERE ON 12/31/01 THERE WAS NO OIL ON THE TANK AND THERE WAS NO OIL ON THE DECK RAFTERS, WHICH THERE WOULD HAVE BEEN IF THE OIL CAME OUT OF THE VENT FROM AN OVERFILL. NICK AGREED BUT STILL SAID HE WAS WRITING IT UP AS AN OVERFILL. LEON TOLD HIM THAT THE OIL TANK VALVE THAT WAS IN THE DIRT COULD HAVE BEEN LEAKING FOR A WHILE, WHICH WOULD EXPLAIN WHY THE OIL SOAKED AREA WAS SO LARGE.  WE ALSO BROUGHT IN THE DRIVER THAT DELIVERED THE OIL ON 12-28-01. BOB S. HE STATED THE FOLLOWING: "I MADE THE DELIVERY WITH NO PROBLEMS THAT DAY. I'VE BEEN TO THE HOUSE SEVERAL TIMES IN THE PAST . IT IS A FLAT TANK UNDER THE FRONT DECK. WHEN QUESTIONED ABOUT THE DELIVERY 3 WEEKS LATER. I REMEMBERED THE DELIVERY AND THAT THERE WASN'T A PROBLEM WITH THE VENT ALARM AND NO SPILLAGE AT ALL."

column168: (A - B) TRANSPORT TRUCK TURNED THE CORNER TOO SHARP AND ROLLED THE TRANSPORT AND TRAILER IN THE DITCH.  FIRE AND POLICE DEPT WERE NOTIFIED AND DISPATCHED.  NO INJURIES TO ANYBODY.  SUNDAY DECEMBER 23, 2001 1:30 PM TOM WATSON CALLED TO TELL ME HE HAD TURNED HIS TRUCK OVER AND IT WAS FULL OF FUEL.  HE HAD ALREADY TELEPHONED THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THE POLICE. LOCATION OF THE TRUCK WAS IN A DITCH AT 35TH AND ROSEDALE.  2:15 PM I TELEPHONED JIM RICE AT ENVIRONMENTAL REMEDIATION SPECIALISTS TO REQUEST HELP WITH THE ACCIDENT.  3:00 PM KEN DUCKWORTH OF ERS ARRIVED IN FULL FORCE.  I TELEPHONED RJ TRANSPORTATION TO REQUEST A TRANSPORT.  4:00 PM RJ TRANSPORTATION DISPATCHED ONE OF THEIR DRIVERS, BUTCH HOUSE TO PULL FUEL FROM METRO'S DISABLED TRAILER.  4:15 PM THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ALLOWED CLEANUP TO START.  5:00 PM ERS BEGAN TO REMOVE THE PUDDLES OF FUEL.  THIS FUEL WAS FULL OF DEBRIS FROM THE GROUND.  IT WAS CONTAINED ON A SPECIALIZED TRUCK. 5:30 PM ERS BEGAN TAPPING INTO SIDES OF THE TRAILER.  THE BAFFLES WITHIN THE TRAILER BEGAN TO WEAKEN AND COLLAPSE.  8:30 PM RJ'S TRANSPORT BEGAN TO PUMP FUEL FROM METRO'S TRAILER. column168: (A - B) TRANSPORT TRUCK TURNED THE CORNER TOO SHARP AND ROLLED THE TRANSPORT AND TRAILER IN THE DITCH.  FIRE AND POLICE DEPT WERE NOTIFIED AND DISPATCHED.  NO INJURIES TO ANYBODY.  SUNDAY DECEMBER 23, 2001 1:30 PM TOM WATSON CALLED TO TELL ME HE HAD TURNED HIS TRUCK OVER AND IT WAS FULL OF FUEL.  HE HAD ALREADY TELEPHONED THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THE POLICE. LOCATION OF THE TRUCK WAS IN A DITCH AT 35TH AND ROSEDALE.  2:15 PM I TELEPHONED JIM RICE AT ENVIRONMENTAL REMEDIATION SPECIALISTS TO REQUEST HELP WITH THE ACCIDENT.  3:00 PM KEN DUCKWORTH OF ERS ARRIVED IN FULL FORCE.  I TELEPHONED RJ TRANSPORTATION TO REQUEST A TRANSPORT.  4:00 PM RJ TRANSPORTATION DISPATCHED ONE OF THEIR DRIVERS, BUTCH HOUSE TO PULL FUEL FROM METRO'S DISABLED TRAILER.  4:15 PM THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ALLOWED CLEANUP TO START.  5:00 PM ERS BEGAN TO REMOVE THE PUDDLES OF FUEL.  THIS FUEL WAS FULL OF DEBRIS FROM THE GROUND.  IT WAS CONTAINED ON A SPECIALIZED TRUCK. 5:30 PM ERS BEGAN TAPPING INTO SIDES OF THE TRAILER.  THE BAFFLES WITHIN THE TRAILER BEGAN TO WEAKEN AND COLLAPSE.  8:30 PM RJ'S TRANSPORT BEGAN TO PUMP FUEL FROM METRO'S TRAILER. column168: THIS CUSTOMER(WATTS) CALLED FOR A HOME HEATING OIL DELIVERY ON DECEMBER 25, 2001 CHRISTMAS DAY, BECAUSE THEY RAN OUT OF FUEL AND THE HOUSE WAS FREEZING. THE HUSBAND GAVE THE DRIVER A VERY DIFFICULT TIME ABOUT A HOLIDAY CHARGE FOR A DELIVERY AND THE PRICE OF OIL. A DELIVERY WAS ALSO SCHEDULED FOR THE DAY AFTER CHRISTMAS, THE 26TH, AND THE WATTS FAILED TO CANCEL THIS DELIVERY, THEY ASSUMED WE WOULD DO SO AUTOMATICALLY, ALTHOUGH THE TRUCKS GO OUT BEFORE THE PREVIOUS DAYS TICKETS ARE RECONCILED. THE DAY AFTER CHRISTMAS THE DRIVER PULLED UP TO THE HOUSE, MR. WATTS WAS PRESENT, DID NOT SAY ANYTHING TO THE DRIVER, HE HOOKED UP AND BEGAN TO PUMP. THE TANK TOOK AN ADDITIONAL 15 GALLONS THAT THE DRIVER DID NOT HAVE THE DAY BEFORE. AS THE DRIVER WAS NOT EXPECTING ONLY A 15-GALLON DELIVERY WHEN THE NOZZLE CLICKED OFF A SPRAY FROM THE VENT OCCURRED. LESS THAN ONE GALLON OF OIL WAS AROUND THE VENT PIPE. MR. WATTS CALLED OUR SERVICE DEPARTMENT AND THEY RESPONDED, THREE TIMES OVER THE DAY, TO CLEAN UP THE VENT PIPE. MR. WATTS REFUSED TO PAY FOR ANY OF THESE UNNECESSARY SERVICE CALLS, SINCE THE TRUCK HAD DIAPERS AND DRIVER HAD MOPPED THE OIL FROM THE VENT. MRS. WATTS THEN CALLED MY OFFICE AFTER MR. WATTS REPEATEDLY INSISTED WE WERE NOT RESPONDING TO HIM, AND CLAIMED THAT I AM PREJUDICED SINCE SHE IS A PERSON OF "COLOR" I HUNG UP ON HER. WE DO NOT MEET OUR CUSTOMERS IN PERSON AND I HAVE NO IDEA WHAT COLOR MRS. WATTS IS AND FRANKLY I DON'T CARE. WE ARE NOT PREJUDICED, WENT OUT OF OUR WAY TO RESPOND TO FIVE TIMES BECAUSE THE WATTS LET THEMSELVES RUN OUT OF FUEL. THIS IS A FALSE CLAIM AND DOCUMENTS CAN BE PROVIDED FOR EACH CALL.

column168: I AM RETURNING THE FORM 5800.1 AS REQUESTED YOUR LETTER WAS SENT TO ANOTHER OIL COMPANY, WHICH SENT IT TO BOWMAN PROPANE IN TACOMA, AND THEY SENT IT TO US.  WE PURCHASED BOWMAN OIL IN 2001, AND MADE THIS DELIVERY.  THE AMOUNT, WHICH I SEE WAS A QUESTION WAS UNDER A GALLON, IT WAS NOT OVER FILLED AS THE CUSTOMER REPORTED IT WAS A LIMITED DELIVERY OF 100 GALLONS INTO A 300-GALLON TANK.  THE PROBLEM WAS THE CUSTOMER HAD A BAD VENT AND SPIT OIL OUT AND THE DIVER CLEANED UP TO THE CUSTOMER'S SATISFACTION.  I CALLED THE CUSTOMER TO REPORT TO HIM THAT THE VENT WAS BAD AND HE NEEDED TO HAVE FIXED, WHICH WE COULD DO.  HE REFUSED THAT AND I STATED TO HIM UNDER THE CIRCUMSTANCES, WE COULD NOT DELIVER TO HIM UNTIL IT IS FIXED.  WE HAVE NOT BEEN THERE SINCE.  I AM SORRY IT TOOK SO LONG TO GET THIS REPORT TO YOU, BUT I JUST RECEIVED IT LAST WEEK, I ALSO CALLED YOUR OFFICE LAST WEEK AND YOU WERE OUT.  I ALSO CALLED THIS AM.  I AM STILL SENDING TUESDAY 05/11/04. I HOPE THIS IS WHAT YOU ARE LOOKING FOR.
